parameters.$5: Overwrite the Legal Information file.

parameters.$5: Learn about the Token Sale before its official announcement.
parameters.$7: The developers truly believe in "Security through Obscurity" over actual access restrictions.

parameters.$5: Perform a Remote Code Execution that would keep a less hardened application busy forever.
parameters.$7: The feature you need to exploit for this challenge is not directly advertised anywhere.

parameters.$5: Submit 10 or more customer feedbacks within 10 seconds.
parameters.$7: After finding a CAPTCHA bypass, write a script that automates feedback submission. Or open many browser tabs and be really quick.

parameters.$6: In previous releases this challenge was wrongly accused of being based on CSRF.

parameters.$5: Bypass the Content Security Policy and perform an XSS attack with <script>alert(`xss`)</script> on a legacy page within the application.

parameters.$5: Perform a persisted XSS attack with <iframe src="javascript:alert(`xss`)"> bypassing a client-side security mechanism.
parameters.$7: Only some input fields validate their input. Even less of these are persisted in a way where their content is shown on another screen.

parameters.$5: Access a confidential document.
parameters.$7: Analyze and tamper with links in the application that deliver a file directly.

parameters.$5: Perform a DOM XSS attack with <iframe src="javascript:alert(`xss`)">.
parameters.$7: Look for an input field where its content appears in the HTML when its form is submitted.

parameters.$4: Exfiltrate the entire DB schema definition via SQL Injection.
parameters.$6: Find out where this information could come from. Then craft a UNION SELECT attack string against an endpoint that offers an unnecessary way to filter data.

parameters.$5: Use a deprecated B2B interface that was not properly shut down.

parameters.$5: Find the hidden easter egg.
parameters.$7: If you solved one of the three file access challenges, you already know where to find the easter egg.

parameters.$4: Perform an unwanted information disclosure by accessing data cross-domain.
parameters.$6: Try to find and attack an endpoint that responds with user information. SQL Injection is not the solution here.

parameters.$5: Provoke an error that is neither very gracefully nor consistently handled.
parameters.$7: Try to submit bad input to forms. Alternatively tamper with URL paths or parameters.

parameters.$5: Retrieve the language file that never made it into production.
